---
import SchemaLayout from '../../../layouts/SchemaLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

const subPages = [
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/cyp-inhibition/`,
    title: 'CYP Inhibition',
    description: 'Competitive and mechanism-based inhibitors of CYP isoforms; substrates at risk; landmark interaction pairs with management strategies.',
    icon: '🔴',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/cyp-induction/`,
    title: 'CYP Induction',
    description: 'Nuclear receptor–mediated enzyme induction; rifampin, carbamazepine, phenytoin, and St. John\'s wort as key inducers; clinical consequences.',
    icon: '⬆️',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/transporter-interactions/`,
    title: 'Transporter Interactions',
    description: 'P-glycoprotein, OATP, and OCT-mediated interactions; digoxin-amiodarone, statins-cyclosporine, and metformin anchor pairs.',
    icon: '🚪',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/pd-additive-toxicity/`,
    title: 'PD Additive Toxicity',
    description: 'Pharmacodynamic synergism leading to serotonin syndrome, QT prolongation, CNS depression, nephrotoxicity, bleeding, and myelosuppression.',
    icon: '⚡',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/pd-antagonism/`,
    title: 'PD Antagonism',
    description: 'Pharmacodynamic opposition: β-blockers vs. β2-agonists, NSAIDs vs. antihypertensives, opioids vs. prokinetics.',
    icon: '🚫',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/food-drug/`,
    title: 'Food–Drug Interactions',
    description: 'Grapefruit/CYP3A4, tyramine/MAOIs, vitamin K/warfarin, dairy/tetracyclines, alcohol combinations, and high-fat meal absorption effects.',
    icon: '🍊',
  },
  {
    href: `${base}schemas/09-drug-interactions/protein-binding/`,
    title: 'Protein Binding Displacement',
    description: 'Plasma protein binding, albumin displacement interactions, clinical magnitude of effect, and correction of a common misconception.',
    icon: '🔗',
  },
];
---
<SchemaLayout
  title="Drug Interactions — Schema 9"
  schema="drug-interactions"
  description="A mechanistic survey of pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic drug interactions: CYP inhibition and induction, transporter proteins, additive toxicity, pharmacodynamic antagonism, food-drug interactions, and protein-binding displacement."
>
  <div class="mb-8">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-serif font-bold mb-2">Schema 9 — Drug Interactions</h1>
    <p class="text-base-content/70 text-lg">Pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic interactions: mechanisms, magnitude, and nursing management</p>
  </div>

  <div class="prose max-w-none mb-10">
    <p>
      Drug-drug interactions are among the leading preventable causes of adverse drug events,
      accounting for an estimated 3–5% of all in-hospital medication errors and contributing
      to over 125,000 deaths annually in the United States. The clinical significance of a
      drug interaction is not fixed — it depends on the therapeutic index of the affected drug,
      the patient's physiological reserve, the degree of the interaction, and the availability
      of monitoring or reversal strategies. Understanding interactions at a mechanistic level
      allows the clinician to anticipate, detect, and manage interaction risks before harm
      occurs, transforming pharmacovigilance from a reactive process into a proactive one.
      Nurses, who administer the majority of medications in acute care settings and serve as
      the final checkpoint before drug delivery, carry a unique responsibility to recognize
      interaction signals and act on them in real time.
    </p>
    <p>
      Drug interactions are broadly classified as pharmacokinetic (PK) or pharmacodynamic (PD).
      Pharmacokinetic interactions alter the concentration of a drug at its site of action by
      affecting absorption, distribution, metabolism, or excretion — the four processes that
      govern how much drug reaches the receptor and how long it remains there. The most
      clinically consequential PK interactions involve the cytochrome P450 (CYP) enzyme
      superfamily and membrane drug transporters such as P-glycoprotein, OATP, and OCT,
      which together regulate the biotransformation and tissue distribution of the majority
      of prescribed medications. Pharmacodynamic interactions, by contrast, occur at the
      receptor or effector level and involve additive, synergistic, or antagonistic effects
      without necessarily altering drug concentrations. Both types carry patient safety
      implications, but they require different detection and management strategies: PK
      interactions often manifest as toxic drug levels or therapeutic failure detectable via
      serum drug concentrations or clinical signs of toxicity, whereas PD interactions may
      produce overlapping clinical syndromes that require syndromic recognition.
    </p>
    <p>
      Polypharmacy — the concurrent use of five or more medications — exponentially amplifies
      interaction risk. Older adults are disproportionately affected: the average Medicare
      beneficiary fills 20 or more unique prescriptions annually, and each additional drug
      added to a regimen introduces a combinatorial increase in the number of possible
      pairwise interactions. Age-related physiologic changes compound the risk: reduced
      hepatic mass and CYP activity decrease metabolic clearance, declining renal function
      reduces excretion of renally cleared drugs and their metabolites, decreased albumin
      increases the free fraction of highly protein-bound drugs, and reduced volume of
      distribution for water-soluble drugs increases plasma concentrations. In this context,
      the Beers Criteria, START/STOPP criteria, and Screening Tool for Older Persons'
      Prescriptions serve as evidence-based frameworks for identifying high-risk combinations
      in geriatric patients, and nurses conducting medication reconciliation at transitions
      of care are positioned to apply these tools directly.
    </p>
    <p>
      Nursing's role in drug interaction prevention extends well beyond cross-checking an
      interaction database before administration. Comprehensive medication reconciliation at
      admission, transfer, and discharge — including over-the-counter medications, herbal
      supplements, and recreational substances — forms the foundation of interaction
      prevention, as unrecognized co-medications cannot be screened. During administration,
      nurses must apply knowledge of food-drug and drug-drug timing restrictions: for
      example, separating fluoroquinolones and tetracyclines from divalent cation-containing
      antacids, dairy products, and iron supplements by at least two hours; administering
      warfarin at the same time each evening and counseling patients about dietary vitamin K
      consistency; and recognizing that grapefruit juice, consumed hours before a dose, can
      profoundly inhibit intestinal CYP3A4 and increase exposure to affected substrates.
      The seven sub-sections of this schema provide the mechanistic foundation and clinical
      guidance for each major interaction category encountered in acute and ambulatory practice.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-serif font-bold mb-4">Interaction Categories</h2>
  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 xl:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-10">
    {subPages.map(page => (
      <a href={page.href} class="card card-compact bg-base-100 border border-base-300 hover:border-primary hover:shadow-md transition-all">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h3 class="card-title text-lg">
            <span class="text-2xl mr-1">{page.icon}</span>
            {page.title}
          </h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">{page.description}</p>
        </div>
      </a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="alert alert-info">
    <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="stroke-current shrink-0 w-6 h-6">
      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"></path>
    </svg>
    <div>
      <p class="font-semibold">Clinical Reminder</p>
      <p class="text-sm">All drug interactions should be verified against current clinical pharmacology resources, institutional guidelines, and patient-specific factors including renal/hepatic function, age, and genetic polymorphisms. This resource is educational and does not replace clinical decision support software at the point of care.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</SchemaLayout>
